On our way home from the desert, I convinced Leo Ohtsuki and Brian Daniels to make a brief stop at Prado Regional Park, mostly in the hope of seeing a Ross's Goose that I had missed on my earlier visit.  Though we did see both the Snow Goose and the Ross's Goose, as well as a moderately large flock of Cassin's Kingbirds, our most interesting observation was probably the lack of the hundreds of Bonaparte's Gulls that had been frequenting Laguna Moreno for roughly the past month.  As noted above, our visit was relatively brief, consisting mostly of driving around until we spotted the Ross's Goose, looking at the flock of swallows flying around over the lake, and then doing our best to scan the kingbird flock in search of a Tropical Kingbird that had been seen here about two weeks earlier.  Our search of the park was therefore far from a complete one.  Mostly overcast, mild (5+ knot) breeze, apparently from the south, and in the mid-50s.  3:10-3:40 pm.

LOCALITY: Lake Cachuma - narrows and east end
TRIP COMMENTS: Observers: Melissa Kelly, Dave Compton. --Area covered: Dropped off at the entrance to the Narrows on the south shore (at the northern tip of the peninsula) and birded about 300 m southeast to observation pt. From here, each of us birded at least once over the next three hours to the eastern tip of the peninsula, another 200 m se, while the other observer stayed at our observation point. Our views from the south shore, particularly at our observation point, afforded us good views of the narrows below. We were visiting this location as part of the annual Bald Eagle count conducted on the lake. --Lake conditions: The lake level was approximately 35 ft below capacity. Water extended through the length of the narrows, but there were large areas of mudflats over much of the area. Only a small amount of water and wet ground extended eastward into the east end of the lake. Much of this area was difficult to see from the road along the edge of the lake.

We were on the premises of PRNS all day, so this represents 12 hours of birding. Here are my notes in the records from that day: Full day of hiking and owling. Highlight is a Bobcat in full sunlight in the meadow of the Meadow trail. Bear Valley Trail to Old Pine; Sky Trail to Meadow; Meadow back to Bear Valley (Old Pine is a good uphill, steady but grade is never difficult). Meadow was a steep but safe downhill; the entire hike took 6 hours and was 7.3 miles in length. We then attended a PRBO owling class. Again, after entering this list, I can attest to how much eBird has aided my observational rigor; that not withstanding, this list is complete to the best of my abilities at that time.

Tahoe Keys with Liz West. --My report: On the walk from the Tahoe Keys Marina out to the lake, Liz and I found a few Rufous and one Calliope Hummingbirds feeding along side the path. Out along the shore we found a nice assortment of shorebirds: Western and Least Sandpipers, 3 Semi-palmated Plovers, 1 Snowy Plover, 5 Spotted Sandpipers, and of course Killdeer. Out in the lake itself,  was a Horned Grebe in with the Common Mergs. Later in the afternoon, we found 2 more resting in some reeds. The most difficult bird to ID was the juvenile SEMI-PALMATED SANDPIPER.  We first found it about 10 feet away from us allowing us some excellent close-up looks. Over the course of the next hour, we continued to have a chance for comparisons to the Western and Least SP.
Birded with Liz West on both sides of Tahoe Keys Marsh. Stopped briefly at Taylor Creek area looking for the American Redstart, but only added Willow FC. Stopped briefly at Tallac.

Jeremy Dunford and I camped at the Manzanita Lake Campground (site D-17), arriving in mid-afternoon Aug. 17 and departing mid-day on Aug. 19.  Both mornings, I got up early to walk down to the lake and all the way around and back to D-17 (about 1.5 miles for the full loop, maybe 2.0 miles). Jeremy came with me for an evening walk around the lake. One of the mornings, I walked up the trail toward Lassen Peak for about half a mile and then returned by the same trail.  We also observed birds and mammals around the camp site.  On the 18th, we drove to the start of the trail up to the top of Lassen Peak and hiked to the top and back (about 5 miles roundtrip) during the middle of the day. LOCALITY: Harriett M. Wieder Regional Park, Huntington Beach
TRIP COMMENTS: CAM's notes: After birding Huntington Central Park briefly and finding very few migrants and nothing of note at all (9:10-9:35 am), Brian Daniels and I continued over to check the back part of Bolsa Chica for some shorebirds that had been seen here over the past few days. We ended up spending an extended period of time scanning the shallow pools and associated flats from the bluffs at Harriet Wieder Regional Park. The general lack of habitat in the immediate vicinity, restricted to some Tree Tobacco plants and a small stand of willows along a channel, resulted in our seeing few landbirds during our visit. Also present at times were Doug Willick, Jim Pike, Leo Ohtsuki, Irene Horiuchi, and several others. It was partly cloudy (with most of the clouds concentrated inland from where we were, especially during the latter part of our visit), with a mild (5-10 knot), onshore breeze, and probably in the mid-60s to the low 70s.

LOCALITY: Gazos Creek Rd.--east of Hwy 1 to Cloverdale Rd. Intersection
TRIP COMMENTS: Hooded Warbler (ad. male) was first found here, seen by many in June 04 (singing at that time). Presumed to be long gone, it was a real surprise to find it again calling in great agitation in response to two different N Pygmy Owls calling from nearby points. Crossbills were in single flock as were 8 of 10 WAVI. Most other migrants were dispersed widely, mostly in streamside alders. Quiet for first hour until sun reached the stream.
San Mateo County Big Day for SFBBO Fall Challenge, with Grant Hoyt and Dick Stovall

We rented a boat.  This morning at Lake Cachuma, Jennifer Stroh, Loren Merrill (new UCSB grad student), and I had some great birding.  Only birds seen in close association with the lake are listed here.  Due north of the Marina toward Cachuma Bay we saw a jaeger.  Two photos of this bird are posted on the SB Co. web site.  We also saw 2 Red-necked Phalaropes (photographed also), a Merlin buzzed the shorebirds at Santa Cruz Bay, and 3 Peregrines were seen.  Two of the Peregrines (one adult and a juv) engaged in a lake-wards tumble.  The adult managed to free itself at contact with the water, but the juv just lay there in the water.  As we approached it in our boat, it flopped up and out of the water limping in flight to a snag on the east side of Arrowhead Island.  The adult continued to intimidate by making periodic passes at the distressed juv.  We left before seeing how the drama played out.--Sta Cruz Bay held the best shorebird habitat and the most shorebirds.  We saw 2 Lesser Yellowlegs. Where ever shorebirds were present Least Sandpipers dominated.  Very few ducks are in yet.  --Credit to Halli Pederson who found the jaeger yesterday and to Liz Mason who found a bunch of Rn Phalaropes earlier in the week.
